# File formats:

* SSLBIN \- compiled logic of SSL language. SSL \- text form.  
* SSO \- Object file, contains data in text format similar to JSON. Example: Level scenario, Presets of data.  
* PROP \- Property component. .prop contains data in the same format as SSO. Paired with code. Example of properties: Geometry, Health, Ability User, etc  
* CLS \- Spawnable actor. Collection of properties. The format is the same as SSO. Example: Bullet, Player, Barrel. 

SSO/PROP/CLS data can inherit data from the parent file and override it.  
Example:  
npc\_bot\_marine\_base\_server.cls \-\> Base bot marine with bot logic  
npc\_bot\_marine\_companion1\_server.cls \-\> Chiron bot (abilities overridden, model overridden)

# Actor’s life cycle:

	There are two types of Actors: Poolable and non-poolable. Poolable actors are created once and recycled every time, getting disposed of only at the end of the Level. Non-poolable actors can be spawned in any amount, but it’s an expensive procedure.   
The amount of actors in pool is limited and you cannot have more than that amount of actors spawned at once.

![][image1]

	The amount of actors in the pool is set up per level in the level scenario. Default parameters are defined in archetypes\_librarry.

# Server, Client and Authority

Space Marine 2 is a multiplayer game and most of the entities have server and client parts.  
![][image2]

Client side is mostly Graphics, Visual Effects, Sound, Animations and ping sensitive mechanics.  
Server side is mostly Physics, Logic and data storage for syncing.

# Undefined Behaviour

When a skippable crash happens, like trying to access a NULL actor from the script, the game enters Undefined Behaviour state. It doesn’t crash and continues to work, but behaviour of the game is now unpredictable. It can have no visible effect on the game (VFX didn’t play) or break the game considerably (Scenario execution cancels, game events don’t happen).

# Behaviour Tree

Space Marine 2 AI uses Behaviour Tree technology. Trees are executed on the Server side.  
![][image3]  
Most information can be found on the Internet. In brief: every tree node returns result, either success or failure. Selector executes branches from left to right until success. Sequence executes branches from left to right until failure. Active selector works like selector, but branches on the left of active branch can request execution (Example: got enemy, stop patrol and fight it)

Behaviour Trees have Blackboards \- set of variables to work with. Those variables are either parameters (Cooldown length, fighting range) or passed from external sources (Enemy).  
Nodes get their information from providers. Example: node “Shoot Target” has field “Target” of Object type. In the tree this field is set to “Object Provider: Current Enemy” which will provide node with information about the target to shoot at.

# Blueprints and Scenarios

Most of high level logic is defined through Blueprints, especially Level Scenarios. Each blueprint node can have:

* Execution IN pin. Node will Do Work when this pin gets execution signal  
* Execution OUT pin. This pin will produce execution signal  
* Input data pin. Those pins are connected to other blueprint nodes.  
* Output data pin. When data is requested, this node will Do Work and return value to the requester.  
* Parameter fields. Static values.

![][image4]  
Blueprints in Space Marine 2 are quite similar to Blueprints in Unreal Engine.  
Each node is an SSL Class and Blueprint itself is an SSO file, a collection of node definitions.   
Blueprints also have Blackboards, like Behaviour Trees, to store their parameters and local variables.  
Blueprints can be executed on the Server or Client side. 

* Level Scenarios are blueprints. All level logic defined by a server and client scenario.  
* Actors can have Prop Blueprints and have Blueprints attached to them.   
* Abilities can be designed with blueprints.

# Weapons.

All weapons are defined at firearm\_librarry\_pve.

* Barrel \- an entity that describes how a firearm shoots.  
* Cartridge \- an entity that describes what a firearm shoots.  
* Clip \- amount of ammo.  
* Recoil \- how camera moves when shooting  
* Spread \- projectile direction deviation.  
* UI Description \- ui settings name. Links to ui\_firearm\_librarry  
* Pickup Visuals \- Links to firearm\_describer. Defines how weapon pickup looks  
* Archetype \- server actor of firearm from firearm\_creator\_server  
* Firearm Category \- SMG, Rifle Full Auto, Rifle Semi Auto, Plasma, Pistol, Grenade Launcher, Machine Guns, Special. Perks rely on this field.

Cartridge settings:

* Projectile type \- defines type of the projectile   
* End Effects Type \- defines effects played on hit. Defined at firearm\_describer.  
* Shot Creator Settings \- collection of parameters for projectile, like headshot multiplier, headshot max distance, damage amount, heavy hit damage, penetration preset, etc  
* Penetration Preset \- no\_penetration, average\_penetration (up to 2), heavy\_penetration (up to 5), superheavy\_penetration (up to 10\)  
* Projectile Creator \- projectile creation logic that defines projectile actor, speed, homing settings, etc.

Barrel settings:

* Fire rate \- how fast firearm shoots  
* Shoot logic \- autofire, single\_fire, burst\_fire  
* Trigger Type \- PRESS, RELEASE, CHARGE. When projectile gets shot  
* Charge duration \- how long to charge  
* Is charged auto shot \- firearm will shoot automatically when fully charged

Clip settings:

* Max ammo \- maximum ammo amount in the magazine  
* Reload refund amount \- how many ammo player gets for each reload  
* Infinite ammo \- user have to reload but have unlimited supply of ammo  
* Infinite clip \- user don’t have to reload  
* Ammo consumption \- how many ammo will be consumed each shot (Example: charged plasma and regular plasma)

Aim Settings

* Aim Logic \- blind\_only, knee, scope, scope\_only , scope\_zoom , zoom, zoom\_augmented\_zoom, zoom\_only, zoom\_scope. Defined at firearm\_describer.  
* Zoom FOVs \- list of FOVs for zoom  
* Autoaim settings \- settings responsible for projectile being directed at target.  
* Magnetism settings \- Camera sensitivity around targets

# Melee Weapons

Melee settings are defined at melee\_descriptions\_librarry\_pve. This file has a list of actual melee descriptions. Each melee weapon description is a separate file (Example: melee\_chainsword\_desc)

Melee Description fields:

* Body Desc uid \- model of firearm. Can be empty if melee weapon is a part of character model  
* Health damage, heavy hit damage \- base amount of damage melee weapon does. Each combo defines its actual damage in percentage from base.  
* Owner TPL \- who holds this weapon  
* Melee Detector settings \- describes melee detectors. Melee detector consists of starting bone, ending bone and offsets for each bone.Starting and ending bones can be the same. Bone here is what supposed to hit when melee strike is played. Example, for shoulder attack detector bone is “clavicleR”

Combo parry settings:

* Parry anim link, Riposte anim link, Abort anim link \- record from animation\_table for animation ordering  
* Parry stance anim link \- animation that played on parry stance entering  
* Parry\\Riposte anim link override per enemy \- lets choose animation depending on enemy’s archetype UID  
* Abort strike possibility \- time window allowing to interrupt melee strike with parry  
* Parry enabled duration \- time after entering parry stance that will count as parry  
* Riposte enabled duration \- time after entering parry stance that will count as riposte  
* Parry direction angle \- angle between actor forward and incoming hit direction that will allow parry  
* Riposte damage settings \- damage dispatched onto riposted enemy  
* Combo blueprint desc \- blueprint that describes combos for this melee weapon.Every combo blueprint starts with “Local start” node. Melee Combo Start node have outputs for LIGHT\_TAP and LIGHT\_HOLD. Melee Combo Strike used to play actual attack and have the same output pins. Example:  
  ![][image5]  
* Combo slowdown settings \- may be null. Describe how time slows down on strike  
* Strike Settings. Actual settings that Combo Blueprint uses.  
  * Need ignore inputs and targets \- uses user forward as strike direction  
  * Unconstrainable \- incoming attacks will stop constraining to the actor during melee strike  
  * Constrain offset \- when greater than zero, actor will move towards a point with this offset  
  * Constrain weight \- from 0 to 1, how much actor will be pushed towards offset point. 1 means it’s guaranteed that by the end of animation actor will reach offset point  
  * Target weight \- from 0 to 1, how much target influences constrain trajectory  
  * Rotation weight \- from 0 to 1, how hard actor will rotate towards target  
  * Constrain max linear speed \- maximum speed allowed for actor during constraining  
  * Max damaged actors \- how many actors can single melee strike damage  
  * Animation link \- animation from animation\_table used for this melee strike  
  * Melee detectors \- melee detectors to activate during this strike  
  * Main\\Extra damage settings \- damage applied to struck targets

# Perks

Perks are passive abilities that activate when certain conditions are met.  
Class PerkServer is responsible for perk activation, deactivation and effect. Activation and Deactivation triggers are defined with PerkTrigger. Perk triggers are self explanatory \- a condition for perk to activate or deactivate, example given got hit, got incapacitated, etc  
PerkApplication is an effect of perk. Activation controller describes, how often this perk can be activated.  
Perks are set up in perk\_server\_factory.

# Enemy Spawn Director

 Enemy Spawn Director monitors what is going on during playthrough and controls how enemies spawn \- when, where and in what numbers \- to create the best possible player’s experience.

Spawn points generation: for ESD to work properly every level has to be marked up with potential enemy spawn points. Having a lot of spawn points to consider, ESD decides which of them will be used and when.

* Spawn out-of-view \- spawn points that may be visible by players will be locked to prevent visible enemies spawn. For visibility check the system sees spawn point having “volume” so the point will be considered invisible only if it can actually spawn several enemies all of which won’t be seen at the moment.  
  ![][image6]  
* Spawn distance \- ESD spawns enemies at a certain distance that suits its enemy type and the type of gameplay it reinforces. Enemies with ranged attacks will spawn further from players, but close to the points that provide LOF and desired distance to them.  Melee-oriented enemies will spawn closer to be able to reach players faster  
  ![][image7]  
    
    
    
    
* “Cleared” spawn points \- spawn points that were just seen up close are locked for a certain amount of time. It prevents enemies’ spawn from places player considers “cleared” as he passed them a short time ago. Locking is temporary to prevent situations when in certain circumstances the system is unable to spawn enemies at all.  
  ![][image8]  
* Wave direction \- ESD is trying to choose spawn points that will provide consistent “wave direction” and not just spawn them around players randomly. It means that spawned enemies attack players from general direction, either shooting him from a distance or coming for a melee attack. This feature provides more controllable combat experience making it’s easier for players to control battlefield and not to become constantly outflanked. It also makes it more comfortable to play with a controller as it’s not necessary to turn around too often. Special enemies ignore this rule, so they can produce unexpected and high but short-timed threat.  
  ![][image9]

Special enemies spawn spots \- different types of enemies are allowed to use specific spawn points. It allows to differentiate spawn conditions for different types of enemies. I.e. special enemy that is trying to ambush players can spawn in special positions clinging to walls and ceilings), but other enemies won’t be able to use this spawn points.

Level of threat generated by ESD fluctuates in a cycle of “waves” and “breathers”.  
![][image10]

Tension \- time when players have to be ready for a new combat scene. They can encounter idle enemies (when progressing throughout the level), lesser waves of usual enemies and occasional special enemies.

Wave \- time when players have to actively fight against a wave of incoming enemies. Along with a wave of usual enemies players can encounter special enemies and mini-bosses.

Breather \- time for players to relax after the wave, to heal themselves and search for pickups. Players will encounter almost to none idle enemies (when progressing throughout the level), no waves and no special enemies (excluding those who are trying to ambush players) or mini-bosses.

Swarm Wave \- sometimes Wave stage could arrive in a much more challenging form. Enemies will attack in higher numbers and with higher pressure. This event’s appearance limited by several conditions:

* High cooldown  
* Team stress is not too high (see below)  
* Team is actively progressing through the level (see below)

Maintaining pressure \- usual enemies spawn organized in a way to maintain desired “pressure”. Every enemy has specific “challenge rating” and ESD is constantly trying to maintain desired challenge by controlling the amount of different enemies that are actively combating players in every moment of time.

Enemies are spawning and are attacking players in groups. This way players have constant flow of enemies, but they are not killing them routinely one by one.

ESD will spawn next group when amount of actively attacking enemies became less than desired pressure, so that the pressure will go up to that desired level. This means that during the wave there will be not too much enemies but not too little either.

## Influencing Factors

### **Stress Evaluation and Influence**

ESD constantly monitors how well players are doing and how engaged they are in a combat. The system evaluates team “stress” (median of stress of all players) and modifies enemy spawn to improve players’ experience.

Stress level is increased by:

* Damage taken, incapacitations, getting grabbed  
* Low amount of ammo and other resources in reserve  
* Amount of time player spent in active combat (while doing damage to enemies)

Stress level decreases over time when it’s not increasing.

When team stress is critical (meaning players are outgunned or on the brink of being wiped), the system will consider ending current encounter faster and spawning less enemies, thus giving players a better chance to overcome the challenge.

When team stress is low, the system will try to increase the pressure in the current encounter (more idle enemies if there is no ongoing wave, more enemies in the wave, higher chance to encounter Swarm Wave instead of the usual one).

### **Progress Evaluation and Influence**

ESD also monitors if players are progressing through the scenario or they are stalling. If players are not progressing for any reason, breathers will become longer and waves will become more rare and less numerous.

This allows players to stop focusing on the battle too much and to focus on the objective and progressing throughout the level.

It is considered that players are not progressing, when they are not performing objective-related actions (pressing buttons etc.) and are not entering new areas of the level for some amount of time.

### **Difficulty Influence**

Difficulty level affects enemy spawn in a more direct way. Higher difficulties allow higher pressure value and higher chance of encountering Swarm Wave or a mini-boss at the same stress levels.

### **Amount of Players Influence**

ESD supports ability to play solo without bots if necessary, scaling pressure value accordingly.

## Special Enemies

During Waves and Swarm Waves system can also spawn special enemies to provide high-risk moments, to break up repeatable combat pattern and to create a demand for special reactions and cooperative actions to beat them.

Special enemy spawn defines by:

* Each special enemy type has its own cooldown  
* Amount of specials that can attack players at the same time is limited according to desired pressure value  
* Special enemies that are trying to attack players right away can be spawned only during waves, but special enemies that tend to ambush players can be spawned anytime.

Spawn cooldown and presence limit can be affected by influencing factors (see above).

## Mini-bosses

Mini-boss encounters are a high threat events similar to Swarm Waves. They can only happen 0..2 times per level playthrough depending on how well players are doing. This event’s appearance limited by several conditions:

* High cooldown  
* Team stress is not too high  
* Team is actively progressing through the level  
* Current game area can be used for combat with specific mini-boss

Mini-bosses are especially powerful enemies, such as Neurothrope, Carnifex and Helbrute. Mini-boss encounters are “conditionally sandbox”, which means that they are not pre-paced, but can happen only in specific areas of the levels designed to support this kind of encounters.

## Overrides and Manual Spawn

Level designers can override most important ESD parameters (wave time, breather time, pressure) to implement custom gameplay scenarios and events such as infinite waves etc.

# ESD Manager

esd\_manager consists of two main components:

* Handlers \- execute logic, part of game’s mechanics. Two main handlers are EsdHandlerEnemyPacks and EsdHandlerSpawnAreas. All other handlers are added optionally to the list (EsdHandlerSpecials, EsdHandlerMiniboss, etc)  
* Influencers \- Collect data and adjust ESD parameters

ESD system also contains:

* Base pressure presets  
* Factions and composition presets

EsdHandlerWaves defines Waves and Breathers. Waves can be SHORT, NORMAL, LONG, ENDLESS and SPECIAL. This handler defines each Wave Type’s duration of Wave, Tension and Breather.

All possible enemy packs are described in EsdFactionsAndCompositionsLibrarry.   
EsdHandlerSpawnAreas is responsible for proper enemy pack spawn. All spawn areas are manually placed on the level by designer and consist of idle spawns and aggro spawns.

Influencers:

* EsdInfluencerPlayersCount \- scales difficulty with amount of players (not bots)  
* EsdInfluencerProgress \- evaluates player’s progress. The further players are into the level, the harder it gets  
* EsdInfluencerStress \- evaluates team’s stress level. Time spent fighting, time spent resting, amount of ammo, etc. If stress is high, player will be pressured less. If stress is low, player will be pressured harder  
* EsdInfluencerAlertness \- is responsible for tension accumulation and Tension wave composition. When encounter starts, all Elite and Special enemies will start “Time to Scream” timer. After that timer they scream and players receive tension (Scream Tension Time). When accumulated tension reaches a threshold, Wave starts.

EsdFactionsAndCompositionsLibrarry:  
Each Pack Variant consists of its type (ALL, IDLE, AGGRO) and combat type (RANGED, MELEE). Pack Composition describes what enemy archetypes and in what amount get into that pack. Pack to spawn is chosen by Handler Enemy Packs and pack’s Interest Processor. Interest is accumulated with time by a discrete amount. When pack with highest interest is chosen, its accumulated interest is reset to zero.

Base Pressure Presets determine WAVE pressure depending on chosen difficulty.

# Res3 

Res3 is Saber’s internal resource system.   
Resource file contains:

* Link to a blob (Binary Large OBject) \- file with actual data. \<texture\_name\>.ptc.resource links to \<texture\_name\>.ptc.resource  
* Link to another resource.  
* Additional information

Resource loading:  
On the game’s boot, there are core resources that are loaded

* res://initial/initial.resource \- collection of mandatory resources that are always loaded on the game’s start  
* res://initial/video\_init.initial.resource \- Textures and shader cache. Loaded at video initialization  
* res://ssl/main.ssl/main.ssl.resource \- Main SSL script that is executed after initial resource loading  
* On connection res://initial/initial\_replicas\_all\_client.resource is loaded for client.  
* At the scene start res://scenes/\<scene\_name\>.scn/\<scene\_name\>.scn.resource is loaded

Resource Tag is an unique identifier for each resource, akin to a virtual path. Example being `res://scenes/story_last_stand.scn/story_last_stand.scn.resource`
